                        <span class="s2">&quot;*&quot;</span><span class="o">:</span> <span class="s2">&quot;{{short description|American comic book, animation, television and film writer}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Bates during an interview in 1974.\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1948\n| birth_place   = Pennsylvania\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| area          = \n| write         = y\n| alias         = \n| notable works = &#39;&#39;[[Action Comics]]&#39;&#39;&lt;br&gt;&#39;&#39;[[Captain Atom]]&#39;&#39;&lt;br&gt;&#39;&#39;[[The Flash (comic book)|The Flash]]&#39;&#39;&lt;br&gt;&#39;&#39;[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]&#39;&#39;\n| awards        = \n| subcat        = American\n}}\n\n&#39;&#39;&#39;Cary Bates&#39;&#39;&#39; (born 1948)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url= http://comics.lib.msu.edu/rri/brri/batd.htm|title= \&quot;Batdance\&quot; to \&quot;Bateson,\&quot; Reading Room Index to the Comic Art Collection|date= n.d.|location= East Lansing, Michigan|publisher= [[Michigan State University Libraries]] Special Collections|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160305073907/http://comics.lib.msu.edu/rri/brri/batd.htm|archivedate= March 5, 2016|url-status= live}}&lt;/ref&gt; is an [[Americans|American]] [[comic book]], [[animation]], television and film [[script (comics)|writer]]. He is best known for his work on &#39;&#39;[[The Flash (comic book)|The Flash]]&#39;&#39; and &#39;&#39;[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]&#39;&#39;.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early career===\nBates began submitting ideas for comic book covers to [[DC Comics]] at the age of 13, and a number of them were bought and published, the first as the cover to &#39;&#39;[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]&#39;&#39; #167 (Feb. 1964).&lt;ref name=\&quot;GCD\&quot;&gt;{{gcdb|type=writer|search=Cary+Bates|title=Cary Bates}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=\&quot;Eury\&quot;&gt;{{cite journal|last = Eury (ed.)|first = Michael|authorlink = Michael Eury|title = A Super Salute to Cary Bates|journal= [[Back Issue!]]|issue = 62|pages = 18\u201319|publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date = February 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}&lt;/ref&gt; Bates began to sell stories to DC when he was 17.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2005/06/03/comic-book-urban-legend-revealed-1/ |title=Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #1 |first=Brian |last=Cronin |date=June 3, 2005 |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/663AwVUSk?url=http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2005/06/03/comic-book-urban-legend-revealed-1/ |archivedate=March 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=March 9, 2012 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.wtv-zone.com/silverager/interviews/bates.shtml|title= Cary Bates Interview|first= Bryan D.|last= Stroud|date= October 14, 2011|publisher= The Silver Age Sage|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120829050145/http://www.wtv-zone.com/silverager/interviews/bates.shtml|archivedate= August 29, 2012|url-status= live}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nBates is best known for his work for DC Comics on such titles as &#39;&#39;[[Action Comics]]&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;[[Captain Atom]]&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;[[The Flash (comic book)|The Flash]]&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;[[Superboy (comic book)|Superboy and the Legion of Super-Heroes]]&#39;&#39;, and &#39;&#39;Superman&#39;&#39;. He began working for the publisher in 1963 and continued to do so until the early 1990s. Among his contributions to the Superman mythos, he and artist [[Curt Swan]] co-created the [[supervillain]]s [[Terra-Man]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=McAvennie|first= Michael|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1970s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |location= London, United Kingdom|isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 150 |quote = Scripter Cary Bates and artist Curt Swan chose an inopportune time for Superman to meet Terra-Man, a [[Spaghetti western|spaghetti Western-garbed]] menace who rode a winged horse and wielded lethal alien weaponry.}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the 1970s version of the [[Toyman#Jack Nimball|Toyman]]&lt;ref&gt;McAvennie \&quot;1970s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 158: \&quot;Writer Cary Bates and artist Curt Swan gave Superman all the &#39;fun&#39; he could handle with the savvy new Toyman in &#39;&#39;Action Comics&#39;&#39; #432.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; as well as the [[superhero]] [[Vartox]].&lt;ref&gt;McAvennie \&quot;1970s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 161: \&quot;Fans of John Boorman&#39;s 1974 sci-fi film &#39;&#39;[[Zardoz]]&#39;&#39;, starring Sean Connery in revealing red spandex, could appreciate writer Cary Bates and artist Curt Swan&#39;s inspiration for Vartox of Valeron.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;  In November 1972, Bates and artist [[Art Saaf]] launched the first &#39;&#39;[[Supergirl (comic book)|Supergirl]]&#39;&#39; series.&lt;ref&gt;McAvennie \&quot;1970s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 153: \&quot;Following a decade of back-up action and three years headlining &#39;&#39;Adventure Comics&#39;&#39;, Supergirl finally starred in her own series. For the inaugural issue, Cary Bates and artist Art Saaf enrolled Linda Danvers in college.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; Bates wrote two stories which featured a superhero wedding. In &#39;&#39;[[Superboy (comic book)|Superboy Starring the Legion of Super-Heroes]]&#39;&#39; #200 (Feb. 1974), the characters [[Bouncing Boy]] and [[Luornu Durgo|Duo Damsel]] were married&lt;ref&gt;McAvennie \&quot;1970s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 159: \&quot;Bouncing Boy and Duo Damsel became the first Legionnaires to tie the knot. The wedding planners were writer Cary Bates and artist Dave Cockrum.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; and &#39;&#39;[[Justice League|Justice League of America]]&#39;&#39; #121 (Aug. 1975) featured the marriage of [[Adam Strange]] and the character&#39;s longstanding love interest Alanna.&lt;ref&gt;McAvennie \&quot;1970s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 165: \&quot;In August&#39;s &#39;&#39;Justice League of America&#39;&#39; #121, Adam Strange said &#39;I do&#39; to his long-time love, Alanna, in a story by scripter Cary Bates and artist Dick Dillin.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; &#39;&#39;Superman&#39;&#39; #300 (June 1976) featured an out-of-[[Continuity (fiction)|continuity]] story by Bates and [[Elliot S. Maggin]] which imagined the infant Superman landing on Earth in 1976 and becoming a superhero in 2001. The tale was an inspiration for [[Mark Millar]]&#39;s &#39;&#39;[[Superman: Red Son]]&#39;&#39; limited series published in 2003.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last = Stroud|first = Bryan D.|title = &#39;&#39;Superman&#39;&#39; #300|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 69|pages = 31\u201333|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = December 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}&lt;/ref&gt; Bates would end the marriage of another character when he wrote &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; #275 (July 1979) wherein the title character&#39;s wife, [[Iris West Allen]] was killed.&lt;ref&gt;McAvennie \&quot;1970s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 182: \&quot;Life for the Fastest Man Alive screeched to a halt after writer Cary Bates and artist Alex Saviuk played &#39;The Last Dance&#39; for the Flash&#39;s wife, Iris West Allen.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nBates [[List of comics creators appearing in comics|appeared in his own comics as himself]] several times, alongside superheroes such as the [[Silver Age of Comic Books|Silver Age]] version of the Flash&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic| writer= Bates, Cary| penciller= [[Irv Novick|Novick, Irv]]| inker= [[Tex Blaisdell|Blaisdell, Tex]]| story= The Day I Saved the Life of the Flash| title= The Flash|issue= 228| date= July\u2013August 1974| publisher= DC Comics}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the Justice League of America.&lt;ref name=\&quot;Eury\&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic| writer= Bates, Cary; [[Elliot S. Maggin|Maggin, Elliot S.]]| penciller= [[Dick Dillin|Dillin, Dick]]| inker= [[Frank McLaughlin (artist)|McLaughlin, Frank]] | story= Where on Earth Am I?| title= Justice League of America| issue= 123| date= October 1975| publisher= DC Comics}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite comic| writer= Bates, Cary; Maggin, Elliot S.| penciller= Dillin, Dick| inker=  McLaughlin, Frank| story= Avenging Ghosts of the Justice Society!| title= Justice League of America| issue= 124| date= November 1975| publisher= DC Comics}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\n===1980s===\nBates and artist [[Kurt Schaffenberger]] were the creative team for &#39;&#39;The New Adventures of Superboy&#39;&#39;, a series debuting in January 1980, which took the character out of the Legion of Super-Heroes and back into solo adventures.&lt;ref&gt;Manning, Matthew K. \&quot;1980s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 186: \&quot;After recently departing the pages of &#39;&#39;Superboy and the Legion of Super-Heroes&#39;&#39;, Superboy was free to pursue his own adventures...in this premiere issue written by Cary Bates and illustrated by Kurt Schaffenberger.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; He and artist [[Carmine Infantino]] crafted a Batman backup story for &#39;&#39;[[Detective Comics]]&#39;&#39; #500 (March 1981).&lt;ref&gt;Manning \&quot;1980s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 193&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last = Greenberger|first = Robert|authorlink= Robert Greenberger|title = Memories of &#39;&#39;Detective Comics&#39;&#39; #500|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 69|pages = 54\u201357|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = December 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}&lt;/ref&gt; Infantino returned to &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; title with issue #296 (April 1981) and he and Bates collaborated on the series, including issue #300 (Aug. 1981) which was in the [[Dollar Comics]] format&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last = Weiss|first = Brett|title = &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; #300|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 69|pages = 58\u201360|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = December 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}&lt;/ref&gt; until its cancellation with issue #350 (October 1985). A major shakeup occurred when The Flash would inadvertently kill his wife&#39;s murderer, the [[Professor Zoom|Reverse-Flash]], in &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; #324 (Aug. 1983).&lt;ref&gt;Manning \&quot;1980s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 203: \&quot;Written by Cary Bates, with art by Flash legend Carmine Infantino, the story saw...[the Flash] accidentally break the Reverse-Flash&#39;s neck.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;  This led to an extended storyline titled \&quot;The Trial of the Flash\&quot; in which the hero must face the repercussions of his actions.  Bates became the editor as well as the writer of &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; title during this time and oversaw it until its cancellation in 1985.&lt;ref&gt;{{gcdb|type=editor|search= Cary+Bates|title= Cary Bates (editor)}}&lt;/ref&gt; \&quot;The Trial of the Flash\&quot; was collected in a volume of the &#39;&#39;[[Showcase Presents]]&#39;&#39; series in 2011.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book| last = Bates| first = Cary| title = Showcase Presents: Trial of the Flash| publisher = DC Comics| year = 2011| pages = 592| isbn = 1-4012-3182-9}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nHis final Superman stories were \&quot;Trapped in IMP-TV\&quot; in &#39;&#39;Superman&#39;&#39; #421 and \&quot;Superman for a Day\&quot; in &#39;&#39;Action Comics&#39;&#39; #581 (both [[cover date]]d July 1986).&lt;ref name=\&quot;GCD\&quot; /&gt; Bates was one of the contributors to the &#39;&#39;[[DC Challenge]]&#39;&#39; limited series in 1986.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last= Greenberger|first= Robert|title= It Sounded Like a Good Idea at the Time: A Look at the &#39;&#39;DC Challenge!&#39;&#39;|journal= Back Issue!|issue= 98|page= 42|publisher= TwoMorrows Publishing|date= August 2017|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1987 and 1988, he wrote some stories for [[Marvel Comics]]&#39; [[New Universe]] line and created the &#39;&#39;[[Video Jack]]&#39;&#39; series at [[Epic Comics]] with [[Keith Giffen]].&lt;ref name=\&quot;GCD\&quot; /&gt;  His post-Superman work for DC included a &#39;&#39;[[Captain Atom]]&#39;&#39; series with [[Pat Broderick]]&lt;ref&gt;Manning \&quot;1980s\&quot; in Dolan, p. 229: \&quot;March [1987] debuted the new Captain Atom in his first DC series, by writer Cary Bates and penciler Pat Broderick.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; and the &#39;&#39;[[Silverblade]]&#39;&#39; limited series with [[Gene Colan]].&lt;ref name=\&quot;GCD\&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=\&quot;Eury\&quot; /&gt;\n\n===Later career and other work===\nHis other work includes the [[comic strip]]s &#39;&#39;[[Lone Ranger (comics)|The Lone Ranger]]&#39;&#39; (1980\u20131983),&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|title = Bates and Heath Premiere &#39;&#39;Lone Ranger&#39;&#39; - NY Times Syndicate Revives Classic Comic Strip|magazine = Comics Feature|issue = 12/13&lt;!--this was a double issue hence the unusual numbering--&gt;|page = 21|publisher = [[New Media/Irjax|New Media Publishing]]|date = September\u2013October 1981}}&lt;/ref&gt; &#39;&#39;[[Buck Rogers|Buck Rogers in the 25th Century]]&#39;&#39; (1981\u20131983), and [[Gargoyles (TV series)|Disney&#39;s &#39;&#39;Gargoyles&#39;&#39;]] during the 1990s. In 2008 he returned after a 20-year absence to Marvel and wrote &#39;&#39;[[True Believers (comics)|True Believers]]&#39;&#39;, a limited series about a team trying to uncover secrets in the Marvel Universe.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&amp;id=17324|first= Dave|last= Richards|title= Keep &#39;Em Honest: Bates on &#39;True Believers|publisher= Comic Book Resources|date= July 21, 2008|archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/65I4afB7W?url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&amp;id=17324|archivedate= February 8, 2012|accessdate= February 7, 2012|url-status= live}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nHe was head scriptwriter on the 1988\u20131992 live action [[Superboy (TV series)|&#39;&#39;Superboy&#39;&#39; television series]],&lt;ref name=\&quot;Eury\&quot; /&gt; and co-wrote (with [[Mario Puzo]] and [[John Briley]]) the 1992 film &#39;&#39;[[Christopher Columbus: The Discovery]]&#39;&#39;, produced by &#39;&#39;[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman: The Movie]]&#39;&#39; producers [[Alexander Salkind|Alexander]] and [[Ilya Salkind]].\n\nBates made a return to writing Superman, this time as an [[Elseworlds]] story titled &#39;&#39;Superman: The Last Family of Krypton&#39;&#39;, published in August 2010.&lt;ref name=\&quot;GCD\&quot; /&gt; Bates worked on the DC Comics nostalgic event &#39;&#39;[[DC Retroactive]]&#39;&#39; writing stories for the [[One-shot (comics)|one-shot]] specials &#39;&#39;DC Retroactive: Flash - The &#39;70s&#39;&#39; (with art by Benito Gallego and [[Sal Buscema]]), and &#39;&#39;DC Retroactive: JLA - The &#39;70s&#39;&#39; (drawn by [[Gordon Purcell]] and Andy Smith), both released with September 2011 cover dates.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/comics/cary-bates-retroactive-flash-jla-earth-prime-110711.html |title=Cary Bates Flash-es Back, Visits Retro Earth-Prime |first=Vaneta |last=Rogers |date=July 11, 2011 |publisher=[[Newsarama]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/663Bv3Mvo?url=http://www.newsarama.com/comics/cary-bates-retroactive-flash-jla-earth-prime-110711.html |archivedate=March 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=March 9, 2012 }}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\n==Bibliography==\nComics work includes:\n\n===DC Comics===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n\n*&#39;&#39;[[Action Comics]]&#39;&#39; ([[Superman]]): #354, 356, 358, 366-370, 383-390, 392, 401, 403, 405, 407-408, 410, 412, 414-416, 419, 421-423, 425-428, 430-435, 438-439, 441-442, 444-446, 450, 453-454, 456, 460-466, 468-476, 480-485, 487-499, 501-512, 544, 548-549, 581 (1967\u20131986)\n*&#39;&#39;[[Adventure Comics]]&#39;&#39; ([[Supergirl (Kara Zor-El)|Supergirl]]): #381-382, 384, 386, 388-389, 391-392, 394, 396; ([[Vigilante (comics)|Vigilante]]): #426-427; ([[Flash (Barry Allen)|The Flash]]): #459-466 (1969\u20131979)\n*&#39;&#39;[[Captain Atom]]&#39;&#39; #1-46, 50, &#39;&#39;Annual&#39;&#39; #1-2 (1987\u20131991)\